        "title": "Extreme-risk stress test for steel stampings and tier-1 assemblies supply dependencies",
        "ref": "S27 — Black Swan Analysis",
        "feature": "Black Swan Analysis (S27)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Commodity Manager conducting a strategic risk review wants to understand the organisation's exposure to low-probability, high-impact events in steel stampings and tier-1 assemblies — the scenarios that are not on the standard risk register precisely because they feel unlikely. A regulator, insurer, or board has asked for evidence that extreme scenarios have been considered.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S27 — Black Swan Analysis. In Block 1, describe the strategic scope of the analysis: the category or supply chain being stress-tested, whether you are examining a single category or end-to-end supply chain, and the regulatory or governance driver for the exercise. In Block 2, define your supply chain's critical dependencies: the strategic nodes where a single point of failure would halt operations — sole-source suppliers, geographic chokepoints, logistics routes with no alternative, or regulatory approvals that cannot be transferred. In Block 3, provide your resilience baseline: current buffer stock levels, documented alternative supplier options, and any business continuity provisions already in your contracts.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured Black Swan analysis identifying the top extreme-risk scenarios specific to your steel stampings and tier-1 assemblies supply chain, with each scenario assessed for plausibility (low-probability signals that already exist in the market), potential impact magnitude, and the specific supply chain nodes that would be most affected. For each scenario, EXOS provides pre-emptive resilience strategies — actions you can take now, before the event occurs, to reduce vulnerability — and a decision tree for response if the scenario begins to develop.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Black Swan events, by definition, are the ones your standard risk process doesn't prepare you for. But they are rarely completely unpredictable — they are events that had visible precursor signals that risk teams chose not to take seriously. COVID-19 supply chain disruptions, the Suez Canal blockage, and European energy market shocks all had identifiable precursor indicators years before they materialised. EXOS uses real-time market intelligence to identify current precursor signals in your specific supply chain, giving risk leaders the early warning they need to build resilience before resilience is urgently required.",
