        "title": "Multi-scenario procurement budget for specialty chemicals and packaging",
        "ref": "S6 — Forecasting & Budgeting",
        "feature": "Forecasting & Budgeting",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Category Specialist is building the annual procurement budget for specialty chemicals and packaging and faces the same pressure every year: Finance wants a single number, but procurement knows that commodity volatility, FX exposure, and supplier market dynamics make any single-point forecast unreliable. The team is manually adjusting last year's budget by an inflation estimate and calling it a plan.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S6 — Forecasting & Budgeting. In Block 1, provide your industry and the specific category or categories in scope. In Block 2, enter your historical spend data for the category — at minimum, the last 12 months of actual spend, current contracted volumes, and the primary commodity or cost indices that drive the category price. In Block 3, add the macro-economic risk factors most relevant to your category: expected volume changes, known contract renewals or re-tenders in the forecast period, FX exposure if you buy in non-functional currency, and any regulatory changes that could affect cost (e.g. new EU tariffs, emissions regulations affecting transport).\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A three-scenario procurement budget model — Base Case (most likely trajectory), Optimistic Case (favourable market conditions), and Pessimistic Case (adverse macro scenario). Each scenario is built on explicit assumptions, not opaque black-box adjustments. The output includes a variance analysis against your historical trend, a sensitivity table identifying which input assumptions drive the widest budget range, and a risk-adjusted budget recommendation you can defend to Finance with clear reasoning.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Procurement budgets built on flat-line extrapolation consistently miss when commodity markets move. The average procurement budget variance in commodity-exposed categories is 12–18% against plan. EXOS uses real-time commodity index grounding via its Perplexity integration to compensate for missing benchmark data, ensuring your budget reflects where the market is heading — not just where it has been.",
        "teachingPoint": "The most important input is your historical spend data for the category — at minimum 12 months of actuals. EXOS will automatically pull current commodity index data via its real-time grounding layer, but you need to specify which indices are most relevant to your category in Block 3. Even if you don't know the exact index name, describing the primary input (e.g. 'aluminium spot price', 'European road freight rates') is sufficient.",
        "hook": "Procurement budgets built on flat-line inflation adjustments miss by 12–18% in commodity-exposed categories. EXOS builds a three-scenario budget model — Base, Optimistic, and Pessimistic — grounded in real-time commodity indices, so your annual plan reflects market reality and you can defend every assumption to Finance.",
