        "title": "Probability-impact risk heat map for structural steel and specialist subcontractors",
        "ref": "S18 — Risk Matrix",
        "feature": "Risk Matrix (S18)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Project Procurement Manager has a risk register — perhaps generated via S17, or compiled manually — and needs to present it visually to a risk governance committee. The committee needs to understand which risks demand immediate action and which can be tolerated, but a table of risks with text descriptions does not communicate priority with the same clarity as a visual heat map.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S18 — Risk Matrix. In Block 1, describe the risk governance context: is this for a procurement category review, a board-level risk presentation, a project risk assessment, or an annual supplier risk audit? In Block 2, provide your risk list — a minimum of 5 identified risks with a brief description of the threat for each. For each risk, provide your probability rating (High/Medium/Low or a numeric 1–5 scale) and impact rating on the same scale. Without these ratings, EXOS applies conservative defaults but flags them with reduced confidence — the matrix will have lower credibility with auditors. In Block 3, add the risk category for each item (Operational, Financial, Compliance, or Strategic) and any existing control measures already in place.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A 5×5 probability-impact risk matrix with all risks plotted on the grid, colour-coded severity zones (Green = Accept, Amber = Monitor, Red = Act), a recommended response strategy for each quadrant (Accept / Mitigate / Transfer / Avoid), a prioritised action list ordered by combined risk score, and a risk owner assignment recommendation. The output is formatted for inclusion in board-level risk reports and is exportable for governance documentation.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Risk matrices work because they make priority immediately visible — a risk in the top-right Red zone needs a response plan before the next board meeting; a risk in the bottom-left Green zone can be monitored quarterly. Without the matrix, committees spend disproportionate time on the risks that are most loudly articulated rather than those that are most likely to cause the greatest damage. EXOS ensures your risk committee is looking at the right things — in the right order.",
        "teachingPoint": "A risk matrix is only as credible as its probability and impact ratings. Do not leave these as 'High' without justification — provide the reasoning behind each rating in Block 3, even briefly. If you have run S17 — Risk Assessment first, you can feed its output directly into S18 as a connected workflow: the risk descriptions and ratings from S17 map directly to S18's Block 2 inputs.",
        "hook": "A risk table tells a committee what the risks are. A risk matrix shows them where to act. EXOS generates a colour-coded, 5×5 probability-impact heat map from your risk register in minutes — complete with response strategies per quadrant and a prioritised action list. Your risk governance committee gets visual clarity, not document fatigue.",
