        "title": "Supply disruption response plan for structural steel and specialist subcontractors",
        "ref": "S26 — Disruption Management",
        "feature": "Disruption Management (S26)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Project Procurement Manager is dealing with an active or emerging supply disruption affecting structural steel and specialist subcontractors — a supplier has notified force majeure, a geopolitical event has closed a key trade corridor, or a quality issue has suspended a critical sole-source supplier. The organisation needs a structured response plan within hours, not days.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S26 — Disruption Management. In Block 1, describe the disruption event: what has happened, which category and suppliers are affected, and what the current operational impact is on your business. Be specific about the nature of the disruption — supply shortfall, logistics failure, quality halt, or regulatory enforcement action. In Block 2, describe the affected procurement scope: the categories and volumes at risk, your current inventory cover, alternative supplier options you are aware of, and any contractual obligations (SLAs, delivery commitments to customers) that are now at risk. In Block 3, provide the strategic context: the duration you are prepared to manage in emergency mode, your authorisation level for emergency spend, and key stakeholders who need to be kept informed.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured disruption response plan covering three phases: Immediate Containment (actions in the first 72 hours), Supply Continuity (interim sourcing options, bridge stock solutions, and demand-side mitigation), and Recovery (restoring normal supply without creating new single-point dependencies). The plan includes a stakeholder communication brief, a decision log template for audit trail purposes, and a risk escalation framework showing at what point the response needs to move to executive level.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Supply disruptions are expensive precisely because response decisions made under time pressure, without a structured framework, tend to be costly and irreversible. Emergency spot purchases carry 30–80% price premiums; expedited freight adds 200–400% on normal shipping costs; and a poorly managed disruption that reaches your customers carries reputational and contractual penalty costs that dwarf the procurement premium. EXOS turns crisis moments into structured response processes — ensuring the decisions made in the first 72 hours are the right ones.",
        "teachingPoint": "In a live disruption, the quality of your Block 1 input is what drives the response plan's usefulness. Be specific: name the disruption type (supplier insolvency, force majeure, logistics failure, quality recall), the affected volumes and time horizon, and your current inventory cover in days. The more operational detail you provide, the more immediately actionable the containment and continuity recommendations will be.",
        "hook": "Emergency procurement decisions made without a structured framework cost 30–80% more than planned sourcing. EXOS generates a three-phase disruption response plan — Containment, Continuity, Recovery — in minutes, so your team acts with structure instead of panic. Decisions made in the first 72 hours of a supply crisis determine 80% of the total financial impact.",
