        "feature": "Dynamic Monitoring — Price Volatility (DM-2)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Project Procurement Manager managing structural steel and specialist subcontractors spend is exposed to commodity price movements that directly affect the contract cost base — but the team only finds out that prices have moved significantly when a supplier triggers an escalation clause or requests a price review. At that point, the movement has already happened and the leverage to negotiate is gone.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Activate Dynamic Monitoring DM-2 — Price Volatility Monitor. Configure the module by specifying: the commodity indices relevant to your structural steel and specialist subcontractors category (e.g. LME aluminium spot, European natural gas TTF, Baltic Dry Index), the escalation clause mechanisms in your current contracts and the trigger thresholds that activate them, and your annual spend baseline so EXOS can translate price movements into budget impact estimates. Set your comparison period and alert sensitivity based on your planning cycle — typically month-on-month for budget monitoring and week-on-week for categories with rapid price exposure.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A price volatility dashboard showing the current index levels and their Δ movement across your selected comparison periods. EXOS flags when cumulative price movements are approaching escalation clause trigger points, quantifies the budget impact of the observed movement on your annual spend, and models forward scenarios based on current market trajectory. When price movements are significant, EXOS generates a negotiation brief explaining the counterargument to a supplier price increase request — grounded in the same market data the supplier is using to justify the ask.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Commodity price movements are manageable when you see them coming; they are expensive when they arrive as surprises. Organisations that monitor price indices in real time are in a fundamentally stronger position in supplier negotiations — they are reacting to the same data as the supplier, rather than reacting to the supplier's interpretation of data they have not yet seen. EXOS makes real-time commodity monitoring accessible without requiring a dedicated market intelligence function.",
