        "title": "Licence compliance audit for fabrics, trims, and contract manufacturing software estate",
        "ref": "S19 — Software Licensing Audit",
        "feature": "Licensing Audit (S19)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Sourcing Manager has received notice of an upcoming vendor software audit — or, more commonly, is approaching a contract renewal and wants to understand the organisation's true licence position before the vendor does. The gap between what the contract defines as a 'licensed user' and how the organisation actually measures usage is the single most reliable source of unexpected true-up invoices across the industry — and it is almost always larger than the procurement team expects.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S19 — Software Licensing Audit. In Block 1, describe your industry and the strategic importance of the software estate in scope — is this business-critical infrastructure or departmental tooling? In Block 2, provide the licence agreement details: the licensed metric as written in the contract (users, CPU sockets, revenue threshold, or named metric), the current provisioned licence count, the actual active user or usage count from your admin portal or SSO logs, the contract expiry or true-up date, and the current annual contract value. In Block 3, add the metric definition analysis: how the contract defines the licensed metric versus how your internal IT team measures it, any historical true-up invoices from previous periods, and whether the vendor has exercised audit rights previously.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A licence compliance assessment identifying metric mismatches between contract definition and internal measurement methodology, a quantified true-up exposure estimate showing the maximum financial risk at the next audit or renewal, a renewal leverage analysis identifying where negotiation room exists (volume tier thresholds, competitive alternatives, contract term flexibility, licence true-down rights), and a prioritised action plan for licence optimisation before the renewal date. The output explicitly flags any clauses containing audit rights, automatic escalation provisions, or metric re-definition language.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: The licence compliance gap is almost never the organisation's fault — it is the product of contract language designed to be ambiguous, measured against internal systems that were never configured to track the contracted metric. Gartner research confirms 68% of enterprises receive unexpected true-up invoices, with an average overcharge of 15–30% of contract value. On a €500k software contract, that is a €75–150k surprise. EXOS finds the gap before the vendor does — and turns it into leverage rather than a liability.",
        "teachingPoint": "The highest-value input in S19 is Block 3's metric mismatch analysis: the exact wording of your licensed metric in the contract versus how your IT system measures active usage. Pull the vendor's metric definition from the contract (usually in the definitions section or the order form) and your current active user report from the admin portal. This comparison is where EXOS generates the most financially significant insights.",
        "hook": "68% of enterprises face unexpected software true-up invoices — averaging 15–30% of contract value. On a €500k contract, that is up to €150k in avoidable cost. EXOS finds the metric mismatches hiding in your licence agreements before your vendor does, quantifies the exposure, and builds your renewal leverage brief — so you control the negotiation.",
