        "feature": "Make vs. Buy Analyser",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Supply Chain Manager is under pressure to evaluate whether medical consumables and equipment services should continue to be outsourced or brought in-house. The CFO wants a financial model; the COO wants a risk assessment; the board wants a recommendation. The team is spending weeks building conflicting spreadsheets that answer different versions of the question.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S3 — Make vs. Buy. In Block 1, set the strategic context: your industry, the category in scope, and whether the driver is cost reduction, quality control, IP protection, capacity, or supply security. In Block 2, provide the current outsourced cost structure — annual spend, contract terms, supplier dependency level — and the estimated in-house setup cost: CAPEX for equipment or facilities, FTE requirements, and ramp-up timeline. In Block 3, add strategic qualifiers: your core competency boundaries, regulatory constraints on self-manufacture, and the reversibility requirement — how easy would it be to exit the insourced model in 3 years.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured Make vs. Buy analysis across four evaluation dimensions — financial (NPV comparison over the decision horizon), operational (capability requirements and ramp risk), strategic (alignment with core competency and IP exposure), and risk (supply security vs. operational complexity). The output includes a recommended path with the key assumptions it rests on, a sensitivity table showing at what volume or cost threshold the decision flips, and a structured one-page executive summary.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Make vs. Buy decisions made without a structured framework frequently reverse within 3 years at significant cost. The average failed insourcing initiative costs 2.5x the projected setup investment when reversal costs, quality incidents, and lost supplier relationships are included. EXOS ensures the decision is made on the right dimensions — not just the most visible cost line on this quarter's P&L.",
