        "ref": "S7 — SaaS Optimisation",
        "feature": "SaaS Optimiser",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Procurement Director receives a renewal invoice for a major software platform in the food & beverage ingredients and facilities services stack and suspects the organisation is paying for capacity it no longer uses. Headcount has changed, usage patterns have shifted, and the original licence count was agreed two contracts ago — but nobody has formally reviewed it. The renewal is in 60 days and there is currently no leverage.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S7 — SaaS Optimisation. In Block 1, describe your industry and the scope of the software estate you are reviewing — a single application or a broader portfolio review. In Block 2, provide for each application: the contract licence count, the actual active user count (from the vendor admin portal or your SSO logs), the licence tier (e.g. Professional vs. Enterprise), the current annual contract value, and the renewal or true-up date. In Block 3, add the metric definition as written in the contract — how a 'user' or 'seat' is defined — versus how your organisation actually counts it internally, plus any historical true-up invoices or vendor audit activity.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A licence optimisation analysis identifying unused licences and over-provisioned tiers, a true-up exposure estimate quantifying your financial risk before the next audit, a renewal leverage analysis showing where negotiation room exists (volume tier thresholds, competitive alternatives, term flexibility), and a prioritised action list with estimated savings per application. The output flags any contract clauses containing audit rights or automatic escalation provisions.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Gartner research shows that 68% of enterprises receive unexpected true-up invoices, and the average overcharge on enterprise software is 15–30% of contract value. On a €200k contract, that is €30–60k in avoidable cost. The challenge is that vendor contracts are engineered to obscure metric mismatches — the definition of a 'user' in your contract and how your IT team counts active users are frequently different. EXOS identifies those gaps before the vendor does.",
