        "description": "SITUATION: A Ops Procurement Manager is building the annual procurement budget for production services and technology and faces the same pressure every year: Finance wants a single number, but procurement knows that commodity volatility, FX exposure, and supplier market dynamics make any single-point forecast unreliable. The team is manually adjusting last year's budget by an inflation estimate and calling it a plan.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S6 — Forecasting & Budgeting. In Block 1, provide your industry and the specific category or categories in scope. In Block 2, enter your historical spend data for the category — at minimum, the last 12 months of actual spend, current contracted volumes, and the primary commodity or cost indices that drive the category price. In Block 3, add the macro-economic risk factors most relevant to your category: expected volume changes, known contract renewals or re-tenders in the forecast period, FX exposure if you buy in non-functional currency, and any regulatory changes that could affect cost (e.g. new EU tariffs, emissions regulations affecting transport).\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A three-scenario procurement budget model — Base Case (most likely trajectory), Optimistic Case (favourable market conditions), and Pessimistic Case (adverse macro scenario). Each scenario is built on explicit assumptions, not opaque black-box adjustments. The output includes a variance analysis against your historical trend, a sensitivity table identifying which input assumptions drive the widest budget range, and a risk-adjusted budget recommendation you can defend to Finance with clear reasoning.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Procurement budgets built on flat-line extrapolation consistently miss when commodity markets move. The average procurement budget variance in commodity-exposed categories is 12–18% against plan. EXOS uses real-time commodity index grounding via its Perplexity integration to compensate for missing benchmark data, ensuring your budget reflects where the market is heading — not just where it has been.",
