        "title": "Extreme-risk stress test for production services and technology supply dependencies",
        "ref": "S27 — Black Swan Analysis",
        "feature": "Black Swan Analysis (S27)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Ops Procurement Manager conducting a strategic risk review wants to understand the organisation's exposure to low-probability, high-impact events in production services and technology — the scenarios that are not on the standard risk register precisely because they feel unlikely. A regulator, insurer, or board has asked for evidence that extreme scenarios have been considered.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S27 — Black Swan Analysis. In Block 1, describe the strategic scope of the analysis: the category or supply chain being stress-tested, whether you are examining a single category or end-to-end supply chain, and the regulatory or governance driver for the exercise. In Block 2, define your supply chain's critical dependencies: the strategic nodes where a single point of failure would halt operations — sole-source suppliers, geographic chokepoints, logistics routes with no alternative, or regulatory approvals that cannot be transferred. In Block 3, provide your resilience baseline: current buffer stock levels, documented alternative supplier options, and any business continuity provisions already in your contracts.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured Black Swan analysis identifying the top extreme-risk scenarios specific to your production services and technology supply chain, with each scenario assessed for plausibility (low-probability signals that already exist in the market), potential impact magnitude, and the specific supply chain nodes that would be most affected. For each scenario, EXOS provides pre-emptive resilience strategies — actions you can take now, before the event occurs, to reduce vulnerability — and a decision tree for response if the scenario begins to develop.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Black Swan events, by definition, are the ones your standard risk process doesn't prepare you for. But they are rarely completely unpredictable — they are events that had visible precursor signals that risk teams chose not to take seriously. COVID-19 supply chain disruptions, the Suez Canal blockage, and European energy market shocks all had identifiable precursor indicators years before they materialised. EXOS uses real-time market intelligence to identify current precursor signals in your specific supply chain, giving risk leaders the early warning they need to build resilience before resilience is urgently required.",
        "teachingPoint": "The most valuable input for Black Swan analysis is your critical dependency mapping in Block 2 — identify the single points of failure that would stop your operations: which suppliers have no approved alternative, which geographic routes have no backup, which regulatory approvals cannot be transferred to another supplier. These are the nodes where Black Swan scenarios have the highest impact concentration.",
        "hook": "Black Swan events are rarely completely unpredictable — they have precursor signals that risk teams didn't take seriously. EXOS identifies current precursor signals in your specific supply chain using real-time market intelligence, then models extreme-risk scenarios and pre-emptive resilience strategies. Build your resilience before it becomes urgent — not after a crisis has already started.",
