        "description": "SITUATION: A Supply Chain Lead receives competing vendor quotes for heavy equipment and explosives and faces the classic procurement trap — the lowest headline price looks attractive, but the team suspects that maintenance obligations, integration costs, and end-of-life disposal fees are hiding significant value leakage across the contract term.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Open the Scenarios platform and select S1 — TCO Analysis. In Block 1, describe your industry context and the procurement category. In Block 2, enter each vendor's quoted CAPEX, the contract or asset lifecycle in years, annual usage volumes, and any OPEX line items you already know — energy, maintenance, consumables, labour support. In Block 3, add enhanced detail: warranty terms, upgrade obligations, decommissioning costs, and any contractual price escalation clauses. The more cost lines you provide, the sharper the output.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: EXOS decomposes every quote into a standardised cost architecture — CAPEX amortised over the lifecycle, annual OPEX modelled across all years, and hidden cost categories surfaced by AI reasoning. You receive a side-by-side TCO comparison across all vendors with a clear winning scenario, sensitivity ranges showing which cost assumptions most influence the outcome, and a narrative summary ready to present to budget holders.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Manual TCO modelling in Excel typically takes a procurement team 2–4 weeks and still misses hidden cost categories. Organisations that select suppliers on headline price alone routinely face 15–30% budget overruns within the first contract year. EXOS completes the same analysis in minutes, grounded in category-specific cost benchmarks, so your negotiation is anchored on total value — not just the purchase order.",
