        "title": "Kraljic-aligned category strategy for API raw materials and lab reagents",
        "ref": "S22 — Category Strategy",
        "feature": "Category Strategy Builder",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Category Manager has been asked to develop a category strategy for API raw materials and lab reagents to present to the procurement leadership team. A proper category strategy — market analysis, Kraljic positioning, sourcing approach, supplier relationship model, and action plan — normally takes 4–6 weeks of research, workshops, and document assembly. The ask is for a first draft in days, not weeks.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S22 — Category Strategy. In Block 1, describe your industry in detail: the regulatory environment, the operational criticality of this category, your organisation's strategic priorities, and the current state of the supply market as you understand it. In Block 2, provide the category baseline data: annual spend and trend, number of active suppliers and their approximate spend share, current contract status and expiry dates, and your internal customer's satisfaction with the current supply arrangement. In Block 3, add strategic context: supply market disruptions you are aware of, any internal changes that will affect demand (new products, sites, regulatory changes), and your procurement mandate — is this a cost reduction, risk mitigation, or innovation-driving exercise?\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A full Kraljic-aligned category strategy including: a supply market analysis with competitive dynamics and key risk factors, Kraljic matrix positioning with a justified rationale, a recommended sourcing approach (competitive tender, preferred supplier, partnership, or sole source) with reasoning, a supplier relationship model defining how to engage differently with strategic vs. transactional suppliers, quick-win savings opportunities for the next 90 days, and a structured 12-month action plan with owners, timelines, and success metrics.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Category strategies that sit in a folder and never get implemented are a procurement cliché — usually because they took so long to produce that the market had already moved. The value of a category strategy is in its timeliness, not its perfection. EXOS generates a structured, evidence-based first draft in hours, giving your team something concrete to react to, refine with stakeholders, and actually execute — compressing a 6-week process into a collaborative one-week cycle.",
        "teachingPoint": "The depth of your Block 1 strategic context directly determines strategy quality. Go beyond describing what the category is — describe what it means to your organisation: is it a competitive differentiator, a compliance obligation, a cost centre under pressure, or a resilience risk? EXOS will frame the strategy around your declared priority. If you are unsure of the Kraljic position, describe the supply market characteristics and EXOS will determine the positioning for you.",
        "hook": "Category strategies take 4–6 weeks to produce and are often obsolete before they are finished. EXOS generates a Kraljic-aligned category strategy — complete with market analysis, sourcing approach, relationship model, and 12-month action plan — in hours. Your team gets a structured, actionable first draft to react to, refine, and execute, not a blank page to stare at.",
