        "title": "Structured procurement risk register for private-label goods and logistics",
        "ref": "S17 — Risk Assessment",
        "feature": "Risk Assessment (S17)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Buying & Procurement Manager is preparing for a new contract award for private-label goods and logistics and needs to demonstrate to the governance board that a formal risk assessment has been completed. The team knows the risks intuitively but has never structured them into a formal register — and the board's audit committee now requires ISO 31000-aligned documentation before sign-off.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Open the Risk Assessment platform and select S17 — Risk Assessment. In Block 1, describe your industry and the regulatory environment that applies: GDPR if personal data is involved, sector-specific frameworks (GxP for pharma, FCA for financial services), or cross-sector obligations (CSRD, NIS2). In Block 2, describe at least two distinct risks or hazards in the category — their nature, the supply chain context they relate to, and the potential business impact if they materialise. In Block 3, provide enhanced detail: your estimated probability and impact for each risk, any existing controls or mitigations already in place, and the business process or procurement category most affected.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured risk register with every risk categorised by type (supply, financial, regulatory, operational, or reputational), AI-assessed probability and impact ratings cross-validated against your estimates, a prioritised mitigation action plan with ownership guidance, and residual risk indicators showing the expected risk level after mitigation measures are implemented. The register is cross-referenced against the regulatory frameworks you specified in Block 1, flagging any compliance gaps.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Unstructured risk awareness is not a risk register. Audit committees, procurement governance boards, and insurers require documented probability and impact methodology — not a list of things the team worries about. ISO 31000 benchmarks show that organisations with formal risk assessment processes reduce surprise unbudgeted procurement costs by 30–50%. EXOS produces a board-ready, methodology-aligned risk register in the time it takes to write a meeting agenda.",
        "teachingPoint": "The quality of your risk register depends on how specifically you describe each risk in Block 2. Avoid generic categories like 'supplier risk' — instead, describe the mechanism: 'single-source dependency on a Tier-1 supplier in a politically unstable region' is a risk; 'supplier issues' is not. The more specific your risk descriptions, the more targeted EXOS's mitigation recommendations will be.",
        "hook": "Audit committees and procurement governance boards require ISO 31000-aligned risk registers — not a list of things the team worries about. EXOS produces a structured, board-ready risk register with probability and impact ratings, mitigation actions, and regulatory cross-references in minutes. Organisations with formal risk assessment processes reduce surprise procurement costs by 30–50%.",
