        "title": "Commodity price volatility tracking for infrastructure software and tooling",
        "ref": "DM-2 — Price Volatility Monitor",
        "feature": "Dynamic Monitoring — Price Volatility (DM-2)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Finance & Ops Lead managing infrastructure software and tooling spend is exposed to commodity price movements that directly affect the contract cost base — but the team only finds out that prices have moved significantly when a supplier triggers an escalation clause or requests a price review. At that point, the movement has already happened and the leverage to negotiate is gone.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Activate Dynamic Monitoring DM-2 — Price Volatility Monitor. Configure the module by specifying: the commodity indices relevant to your infrastructure software and tooling category (e.g. LME aluminium spot, European natural gas TTF, Baltic Dry Index), the escalation clause mechanisms in your current contracts and the trigger thresholds that activate them, and your annual spend baseline so EXOS can translate price movements into budget impact estimates. Set your comparison period and alert sensitivity based on your planning cycle — typically month-on-month for budget monitoring and week-on-week for categories with rapid price exposure.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A price volatility dashboard showing the current index levels and their Δ movement across your selected comparison periods. EXOS flags when cumulative price movements are approaching escalation clause trigger points, quantifies the budget impact of the observed movement on your annual spend, and models forward scenarios based on current market trajectory. When price movements are significant, EXOS generates a negotiation brief explaining the counterargument to a supplier price increase request — grounded in the same market data the supplier is using to justify the ask.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Commodity price movements are manageable when you see them coming; they are expensive when they arrive as surprises. Organisations that monitor price indices in real time are in a fundamentally stronger position in supplier negotiations — they are reacting to the same data as the supplier, rather than reacting to the supplier's interpretation of data they have not yet seen. EXOS makes real-time commodity monitoring accessible without requiring a dedicated market intelligence function.",
        "teachingPoint": "The most important configuration step is linking your commodity indices to your escalation clause mechanisms: which price trigger in your contract corresponds to which index movement threshold? Once this mapping is established, EXOS can alert you when you are approaching a trigger point — before the supplier formally activates it — giving you negotiation preparation time rather than reaction time.",
        "hook": "Supplier price increase requests should never be a surprise. EXOS monitors the commodity indices driving your category costs in real time, alerts you when escalation clause thresholds are approaching, and models the budget impact — so you are working from the same data as your supplier before they send the email, not after.",
