        "title": "EU regulatory change tracking for infrastructure software and tooling",
        "ref": "DM-3 — Regulatory Change Monitor",
        "feature": "Dynamic Monitoring — Regulatory Risk (DM-3)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Finance & Ops Lead managing infrastructure software and tooling procurement operates in a regulatory environment that is actively evolving — EU sustainability requirements, supply chain due diligence obligations, AI Act compliance for technology procurement, and sector-specific frameworks are all introducing new procurement obligations on accelerating timescales. Keeping track of what is changing, what is already in force, and what will affect current contracts is a full-time job the team does not have capacity for.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Activate Dynamic Monitoring DM-3 — Regulatory Change Monitor. Configure the module by specifying: the regulatory frameworks most relevant to your category and industry (e.g. GDPR, CSRD, EU AI Act, NIS2, REACH, CBAM), your key contract portfolio — the supplier agreements currently in force that would be affected by regulatory changes, and the compliance lead time your organisation requires — how far in advance of a regulatory trigger date you need an alert to enable timely contract updates or supplier re-qualification.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A regulatory change dashboard tracking the legislative status of all monitored frameworks — whether they are in consultation, adopted, in implementation period, or in force. EXOS flags Δ-changes in regulatory status (a directive moves from consultation to adoption, an implementation deadline is confirmed or amended), cross-references the change against your specified contract portfolio to identify specific agreements that may require amendment, and generates a compliance gap brief explaining what the change requires and what procurement action is needed before the effective date.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: The cost of regulatory non-compliance in procurement is not just the fine — it is the emergency contract renegotiation, the supplier re-qualification programme, and the internal audit findings that follow. CSRD supply chain transparency obligations, the Corporate Sustainability Due Diligence Directive, and the EU AI Act all contain procurement-specific obligations that most procurement teams are currently underprepared for. EXOS ensures you are never surprised by a regulatory deadline that was on the horizon for 18 months.",
        "teachingPoint": "When configuring DM-3, be specific about the regulatory frameworks you want to monitor — generic 'EU regulations' will produce broad, low-actionability alerts. Map each framework to the specific procurement categories it affects: GDPR to data processing suppliers, EU AI Act to AI-embedded SaaS, CSRD to your full supply chain for Scope 3 reporting, CBAM to materials sourced from outside the EU. The more precisely you configure the mapping, the more targeted and actionable the alerts.",
        "hook": "CSRD, the Corporate Sustainability Due Diligence Directive, NIS2, and the EU AI Act all contain procurement-specific obligations most teams are underprepared for. EXOS monitors the legislative status of your relevant regulatory frameworks in real time, cross-references changes against your contract portfolio, and alerts you before a compliance deadline becomes a crisis — not after.",
