        "title": "Continuous supplier risk monitoring for ocean freight contracts and port services",
        "ref": "DM-1 — Supplier Risk Monitor",
        "feature": "Dynamic Monitoring — Supplier Risk (DM-1)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Trade Lane Manager manages a portfolio of ocean freight contracts and port services suppliers and knows that risk events — financial deterioration, geopolitical exposure, regulatory enforcement actions — do not announce themselves at the quarterly review. By the time a supplier problem appears in a QBR, the early warning window has already passed. The team needs a monitoring system that surfaces supplier risk signals continuously, not retrospectively.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Activate Dynamic Monitoring DM-1 — Supplier Risk Monitor. Configure the module for your ocean freight contracts and port services supplier portfolio by specifying: the suppliers you want to monitor (by anonymised token or category), the risk dimensions most relevant to your context (financial stability, geopolitical exposure, regulatory compliance, news sentiment), and your threshold settings — at what point does a risk signal become an alert requiring human review. Select your comparison period (EXOS defaults to month-on-month but supports week-on-week, quarter-on-quarter, and year-on-year).\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A Dynamic Risk Score (DRS) dashboard for each monitored supplier, displaying the current risk score and — critically — the Δ (delta) since the last comparison period. EXOS's Δ-First design means the dominant visual signal is always the direction and velocity of change, not the absolute score. A DRS of 62 that was 78 last quarter tells a completely different story than a DRS of 62 that was 55 last quarter. You receive automated alerts when risk thresholds are breached, a narrative explanation of the key drivers behind significant Δ movements, and bridge links to the appropriate point-in-time scenario (S17, S20) for deeper analysis when a signal warrants investigation.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Early warning is only valuable if it is early enough to act. Supplier financial distress, geopolitical events, and regulatory enforcement actions have observable precursor signals — but only if you are looking for them continuously. EXOS monitors so your team doesn't have to — and surfaces the signals that need attention while filtering out the noise that doesn't.",
