        "title": "SaaS licence rationalisation across SaaS licences and cloud services",
        "ref": "S7 — SaaS Optimisation",
        "feature": "SaaS Optimiser",
        "description": "SITUATION: A IT Procurement Manager receives a renewal invoice for a major software platform in the SaaS licences and cloud services stack and suspects the organisation is paying for capacity it no longer uses. Headcount has changed, usage patterns have shifted, and the original licence count was agreed two contracts ago — but nobody has formally reviewed it. The renewal is in 60 days and there is currently no leverage.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S7 — SaaS Optimisation. In Block 1, describe your industry and the scope of the software estate you are reviewing — a single application or a broader portfolio review. In Block 2, provide for each application: the contract licence count, the actual active user count (from the vendor admin portal or your SSO logs), the licence tier (e.g. Professional vs. Enterprise), the current annual contract value, and the renewal or true-up date. In Block 3, add the metric definition as written in the contract — how a 'user' or 'seat' is defined — versus how your organisation actually counts it internally, plus any historical true-up invoices or vendor audit activity.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A licence optimisation analysis identifying unused licences and over-provisioned tiers, a true-up exposure estimate quantifying your financial risk before the next audit, a renewal leverage analysis showing where negotiation room exists (volume tier thresholds, competitive alternatives, term flexibility), and a prioritised action list with estimated savings per application. The output flags any contract clauses containing audit rights or automatic escalation provisions.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Gartner research shows that 68% of enterprises receive unexpected true-up invoices, and the average overcharge on enterprise software is 15–30% of contract value. On a €200k contract, that is €30–60k in avoidable cost. The challenge is that vendor contracts are engineered to obscure metric mismatches — the definition of a 'user' in your contract and how your IT team counts active users are frequently different. EXOS identifies those gaps before the vendor does.",
        "teachingPoint": "The highest-value input is the metric mismatch analysis in Block 3: how does your contract define a licensed user or seat, and how does your internal IT system actually measure it? This single gap is the source of most unexpected true-up invoices. Pull your active user report from the vendor admin portal before running this scenario — even a rough headcount by module is enough to start.",
        "hook": "68% of enterprises receive unexpected software true-up invoices. The average overcharge is 15–30% of contract value — on a €200k contract, that is up to €60k in avoidable cost. EXOS finds the metric mismatches and licence waste before your vendor does, so you walk into renewal with leverage instead of a surprise invoice.",
