        "title": "Performance scorecard for SaaS licences and cloud services supplier review",
        "ref": "S11 — Supplier Scorecard",
        "feature": "Supplier Scorecard",
        "description": "SITUATION: A IT Procurement Manager has a quarterly business review with a key SaaS licences and cloud services supplier in two days. The last QBR was an informal conversation — this time, stakeholders are asking for structure: KPI performance against contract, a clear gap analysis, and improvement targets with accountability. Building a proper scorecard from scratch in the time available is not realistic.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S11 — Supplier Scorecard. In Block 1, describe your industry and the supplier relationship context: how long you have been working together, the strategic importance of the supplier in the Kraljic matrix, and the current state of the relationship. In Block 2, provide the contracted KPIs and targets: delivery performance, quality metrics, service levels, invoice accuracy, and any commercial compliance measures. Enter the actual performance figures for the review period against each KPI. In Block 3, add context: major incidents or disruptions in the period, improvement actions agreed at the last review and their status, and any forward-looking changes in volume or specification.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A structured supplier scorecard with RAG-rated performance against each contracted KPI, a gap analysis identifying the delta between target and actual for every metric, a root cause framing for the most significant underperformance areas, recommended improvement targets and timelines for the next review period, and a relationship health summary categorising the supplier as Developing, Performing, or Strategic. The output includes a QBR agenda structure so the conversation stays focused on evidence, not anecdote.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Supplier relationships without structured performance measurement consistently underperform contracted service levels — suppliers prioritise customers who hold them accountable. Research shows that organisations with formal supplier scorecard programmes achieve 23% better on-time delivery performance compared to those relying on informal relationship management. EXOS turns a reactive QBR into a structured performance dialogue that drives measurable improvement.",
        "teachingPoint": "The most important inputs are the contracted KPI targets and your actual performance data for the review period. If your contracts do not specify numerical KPI targets, describe what 'good' looks like in plain terms — EXOS will propose measurable proxies. Bring actual data to Block 2 even if it is approximate; a score based on real numbers is always more credible with suppliers than a qualitative narrative.",
        "hook": "Organisations with formal supplier scorecard programmes achieve 23% better on-time delivery than those relying on informal relationship management. EXOS generates a structured, RAG-rated performance scorecard in minutes — so your QBR is a focused, evidence-based improvement conversation, not an uncomfortable catch-up meeting.",
        "persona": "IT Procurement Manager"
