        "feature": "Volume Consolidation (S24)",
        "description": "SITUATION: A IT Procurement Manager suspects that SaaS licences and cloud services spend is fragmented across multiple business units, geographies, or legal entities — each contracting independently with the same or similar suppliers, at different price points, with no visibility of the combined volume leverage they collectively represent. The savings opportunity is visible in theory, but the organisational complexity of consolidation has kept it on the 'too hard' list for years.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S24 — Volume Consolidation. In Block 1, describe the organisational structure relevant to this analysis — how many entities or business units are in scope, their geographic spread, and the governance model (centralised procurement, federated, or fully devolved). In Block 2, provide the spend data for each entity or business unit: annual SaaS licences and cloud services spend, current supplier(s) in use, approximate volume or unit count, and current unit price or contract rate where available. If exact figures are not available, category-level estimates are sufficient to identify the consolidation opportunity scale. In Block 3, describe the consolidation constraints: any contractual lock-ins, local regulatory requirements for supplier qualification, business unit preferences or internal politics that affect the consolidation approach, and the timeline within which consolidation is feasible.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A volume consolidation analysis mapping total aggregated spend across all entities, identifying supplier overlap and duplication, modelling the price tier benefits achievable at consolidated volumes (typically expressed as percentage savings at each volume threshold), a preferred consolidation structure recommendation (single contract, master agreement with local call-offs, or framework agreement), and an implementation roadmap with the internal stakeholder alignment steps required to execute.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Volume consolidation savings of 8–18% are routinely available in fragmented multi-entity organisations — and routinely left on the table because the organisational effort of consolidation feels greater than the reward. EXOS changes that calculus by making the opportunity size explicit and the implementation path concrete. When a procurement team can show a CFO that £X million of savings requires Y specific steps with a Z-month implementation timeline, consolidation projects get budget and governance support. Without the analysis, they remain a procurement aspiration.",
