        "title": "Should-Cost benchmark for network hardware and field services negotiation",
        "ref": "S2 — Should-Cost Model",
        "feature": "Should-Cost Engine",
        "description": "SITUATION: A Category Lead is entering a renewal negotiation for network hardware and field services without an independent view of what the product or service should actually cost to produce. The incumbent supplier has anchored the conversation on last year's price plus inflation — and the team has no data to challenge it.\n\nHOW TO USE EXOS: Select S2 — Should-Cost Model. In Block 1, describe the procurement category, the supplier's likely geography of production, and the relevant regulatory context. In Block 2, provide the asset or service specification: key materials or input components, estimated labour content (hours or FTE), production volume, and any known tooling or overhead elements. In Block 3, add market intelligence context: any public pricing indices, recent commodity movements, or known competitor pricing if available. EXOS will supplement your inputs with real-time market data via its Perplexity grounding layer.\n\nWHAT YOU RECEIVE: A bottom-up Should-Cost model breaking down the estimated true cost into materials, direct labour, manufacturing overhead, SG&A allocation, and a reasonable margin band. The output includes a defensible target price range, the key cost drivers most sensitive to negotiation, and a structured negotiation brief explaining where the supplier's margin is and how to attack it.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Procurement teams that enter negotiations without a Should-Cost anchor consistently leave 8–18% savings on the table. Suppliers rely on information asymmetry — they know their cost structure, and you don't. EXOS eliminates that asymmetry. A credible cost model changes the entire dynamic of a supplier conversation: you are no longer reacting to their price — you are proposing yours.",
